## 6. Step 3 — Black-Litterman Posterior Returns

The BL formula blends the prior $\Pi$ with the views $Q$ via:

$$\mu_{BL} = \left[(\tau\Sigma)^{-1} + P^T\Omega^{-1}P\right]^{-1}\left[(\tau\Sigma)^{-1}\Pi + P^T\Omega^{-1}Q\right]$$

Where $\tau$ controls how much weight we give to the prior, and $\Omega$ is the uncertainty in our views.
tau = 0.075  # tau raised to 0.075: views carry meaningful weight (BlackRock range: 0.05-0.10)

# Omega: diagonal uncertainty matrix for views
# Using proportional-to-variance approach (He & Litterman standard)
Omega = np.diag([tau * (P[i] @ Sigma_np @ P[i]) for i in range(k)])

# Black-Litterman posterior formula
tauSigma_inv = np.linalg.inv(tau * Sigma_np)
Omega_inv    = np.linalg.inv(Omega)

M1 = tauSigma_inv + P.T @ Omega_inv @ P
M2 = tauSigma_inv @ Pi + P.T @ Omega_inv @ Q

mu_BL = np.linalg.inv(M1) @ M2
mu_BL_series = pd.Series(mu_BL, index=asset_names, name='BL Return')

# Comparison: historical vs equilibrium vs BL
